const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do probiotic gummies actually work?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Probiotic gummies can be effective when they contain clinically studied strains at evidence-based doses. The key challenge with gummy probiotics is bacterial survivability — the heat, moisture, and sugar in gummy manufacturing can kill probiotic organisms before you consume them. Products that use spore-forming strains (Bacillus coagulans) or acid-resistant strains (Lactobacillus rhamnosus GG) tend to deliver more viable organisms to the intestine. A 2019 systematic review in the journal Nutrients analyzed 45 clinical trials on probiotic supplementation and found statistically significant benefits for antibiotic-associated diarrhea (62% risk reduction), IBS symptom improvement, and immune function enhancement — but only when products contained the specific strains and doses used in the positive trials.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How many CFU do I need in a probiotic?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The optimal CFU (colony-forming units) count depends on the specific strain and intended benefit. Most clinical studies demonstrating probiotic benefits use doses between 1 billion and 10 billion CFU per day. Lactobacillus rhamnosus GG is effective at 1-10 billion CFU. Saccharomyces boulardii shows benefits at 250mg-500mg (approximately 5-10 billion CFU). Higher CFU counts are not necessarily better — a 50 billion CFU product with unstudied strains is less effective than a 1 billion CFU product with clinically validated strains at their studied dose. The most important factor is whether the product delivers viable organisms to the intestine, not the number printed on the label at time of manufacture.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take probiotics with food or on an empty stomach?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Research suggests taking probiotics with a meal or within 30 minutes of eating. A 2011 study published in Beneficial Microbes found that probiotic survival through the gastrointestinal tract was highest when taken with a meal containing some fat, and lowest when taken 30 minutes after eating. The meal buffers stomach acid, increasing the pH from approximately 1.5 (fasting) to 3-5, which allows more probiotic organisms to survive gastric transit and reach the small intestine alive. However, spore-forming probiotics like Bacillus coagulans are naturally acid-resistant and can be taken at any time. For gummy probiotics specifically, the sugar content means most people take them between meals as a snack — this is acceptable for acid-resistant strains but suboptimal for standard Lactobacillus species.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do probiotics help with bloating and gas?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Specific probiotic strains have demonstrated effectiveness for reducing bloating and gas in clinical trials. Bifidobacterium infantis 35624 reduced bloating scores by 44% versus placebo in IBS patients in a trial published in the American Journal of Gastroenterology. Lactobacillus plantarum 299v reduced flatulence and abdominal pain in a 2012 randomized trial. However, probiotics can also temporarily increase gas and bloating during the first 1-2 weeks of use as the gut microbiome adjusts to the new organisms. This initial adjustment period is normal and typically resolves without intervention. If bloating persists beyond 2-3 weeks, the probiotic strain may not be compatible with your individual microbiome, and switching to a different strain is recommended.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between probiotics and prebiotics?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Probiotics are live microorganisms (bacteria or yeast) that provide health benefits when consumed in adequate amounts. Prebiotics are non-digestible fibers and compounds that serve as food for beneficial gut bacteria already residing in your intestine. The most common prebiotics include inulin, fructooligosaccharides (FOS), and galactooligosaccharides (GOS). When a supplement contains both probiotics and prebiotics, it is called a synbiotic — the prebiotic fiber feeds the probiotic organisms, theoretically improving their survival and colonization in the gut. Some products in our guide, like Olly Probiotic + Prebiotic, include prebiotic fiber specifically to support the viability of their probiotic strains after ingestion.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can probiotics help with immune function?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes — approximately 70% of the immune system resides in the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT), and the gut microbiome plays a direct role in immune cell training and regulation. A 2015 Cochrane review analyzed 12 randomized trials with 3,720 participants and found that probiotic supplementation reduced the number of participants experiencing acute upper respiratory tract infections by 47% and reduced the average duration of illness by 1.89 days. Lactobacillus rhamnosus GG and Lactobacillus casei are the most studied strains for immune benefits. The mechanism involves probiotic stimulation of secretory IgA production, enhancement of natural killer cell activity, and regulation of inflammatory cytokine balance in the gut mucosa.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do probiotic gummies need to be refrigerated?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most probiotic gummies are shelf-stable and do not require refrigeration, but this depends on the specific strains used. Spore-forming probiotics (Bacillus coagulans, Bacillus subtilis) are inherently heat-stable and shelf-stable because the endospore protects the organism from temperature extremes, moisture, and stomach acid. Traditional Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium strains are more fragile and can lose viability at room temperature over time. However, gummy manufacturers typically use either spore-forming strains or specially encapsulated Lactobacillus strains designed for shelf stability. Always check the product label for storage instructions. Even shelf-stable probiotic gummies should be stored in a cool, dry place away from direct sunlight and excessive heat.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How long should I take probiotics to see results?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The timeline for probiotic benefits varies by the specific health outcome being targeted. Acute digestive symptoms (antibiotic-associated diarrhea, traveler\'s diarrhea) typically respond within 24-72 hours. General digestive regularity improvement usually appears within 1-2 weeks of consistent daily use. IBS symptom improvement in clinical trials typically requires 4-8 weeks of supplementation. Immune function benefits build over 2-3 months of consistent use. Important note: probiotic organisms generally do not permanently colonize the adult gut — they exert their benefits while passing through and need to be consumed continuously to maintain effects. If you stop taking probiotics, their benefits typically diminish within 1-3 weeks as the supplemented organisms clear from the digestive tract.' },
    },
  ],
};
