    <h2 id="why-probiotics">Why the Probiotic Strain Matters More Than the CFU Count</h2>

    <p>The human gut contains approximately 38 trillion microorganisms — more bacterial cells than human cells in your body. This intestinal microbiome regulates digestion, nutrient absorption, immune function, neurotransmitter production, and inflammatory response. When the microbiome is disrupted by antibiotics, poor diet, stress, or illness, targeted probiotic supplementation can restore balance and measurably improve digestive outcomes, immune response, and even mental health through the gut-brain axis.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">70%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of the human immune system resides in the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT). Probiotic supplementation with clinically studied strains has been shown to <strong>reduce acute respiratory infections by 47%</strong> and shorten illness duration by nearly 2 days, according to a 2015 Cochrane review of 3,720 participants across 12 randomized controlled trials.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The critical distinction in probiotic gummies is not the CFU number printed on the label — it is whether those organisms arrive alive in your intestine. Gummy manufacturing involves heat, moisture, and sugar exposure that can kill 90% or more of traditional Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium organisms before you open the bottle. The best probiotic gummies solve this problem through spore-forming strains, acid-resistant species, and guaranteed CFU counts at expiration rather than at manufacture.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
