        <strong>Strain-Specific Benefits</strong>
        <p>Not all probiotic strains do the same thing. L. rhamnosus GG targets immune function and antibiotic recovery. B. infantis 35624 reduces IBS bloating. S. boulardii prevents C. difficile recurrence. Choosing the right strain for your specific goal determines whether probiotics work for you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Survivability Challenge</strong>
        <p>Stomach acid (pH 1.5-3.5) kills most probiotic bacteria within minutes. Spore-forming strains (Bacillus coagulans) survive gastric transit in a protective endospore. Traditional Lactobacillus strains require acid-resistant encapsulation or must be taken with food to buffer stomach pH.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Prebiotic Fiber Synergy</strong>
        <p>Prebiotics (inulin, FOS, GOS) serve as food for beneficial gut bacteria. Synbiotic formulas combining probiotics + prebiotics improve bacterial colonization and provide substrate for the organisms to proliferate once they reach the large intestine.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>CFU at Expiration vs. Manufacture</strong>
        <p>Probiotic viability decreases over time. A product labeled "10 billion CFU at manufacture" may contain only 1 billion viable organisms by expiration. Products guaranteeing CFU "through end of shelf life" are significantly more reliable than those listing CFU only at manufacture date.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

