    <!-- PROBIOTIC STRAIN GUIDE -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Probiotic Strain Guide: Matching the Right Organism to Your Goal</h4>
      <p>Probiotic benefits are strain-specific — not species-specific. Two different strains of the same species can have completely different clinical effects. Here is a guide to matching the right probiotic strain to your specific health goal.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>L. rhamnosus GG (LGG) — General Gut Health</strong>
          <p>The most-studied probiotic strain (1,000+ clinical trials). Demonstrated benefits for antibiotic-associated diarrhea prevention, acute gastroenteritis recovery, immune function enhancement, and general digestive regularity. The versatile, evidence-based choice for most consumers. Used in Culturelle products.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>B. infantis 35624 — IBS & Bloating</strong>
          <p>The strongest clinical evidence for IBS symptom reduction, including global symptom improvement, bloating reduction (44% vs. placebo), and abdominal discomfort relief. Developed through 20 years of research at the Alimentary Health Centre. Used exclusively in Align products.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>S. boulardii CNCM I-745 — Antibiotic Recovery</strong>
          <p>The only probiotic yeast — naturally resistant to antibiotics and can be taken concurrently with antibiotic therapy. Strongest evidence for preventing C. difficile recurrence (50-60% risk reduction) and antibiotic-associated diarrhea (53% risk reduction). Used in Florastor products.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Bacillus coagulans — Gummy Survivability</strong>
          <p>A spore-forming probiotic that survives manufacturing heat, shelf storage, and stomach acid in a protective endospore shell. Activates in the warm, moist intestinal environment. Clinical evidence for IBS improvement, bloating reduction, and digestive regularity. The most reliable probiotic for the gummy delivery format.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <div class="tip-box-ico"><Icon name="tip" size={18} /></div>
        <p><strong>The initial adjustment period is normal:</strong> When starting any probiotic supplement, mild gas and bloating during the first 1-2 weeks is common and expected. This occurs because the introduced probiotic organisms are beginning to modify the gut environment — producing organic acids, competing with existing bacteria, and fermenting prebiotic fibers. This adjustment period typically resolves without intervention. If symptoms persist beyond 3 weeks or worsen significantly, discontinue the product and try a different strain.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Probiotic Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> All 8 probiotic gummies were purchased at full retail price through Amazon. No brand was informed of this evaluation, and no products were provided as complimentary samples.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified strain identity and CFU claims.</strong> We reviewed certificates of analysis for each product to confirm that the labeled probiotic strains match the actual organisms present and that CFU counts are accurate. Probiotic mislabeling is a documented industry problem — independent testing has found products containing different species than listed on the label.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed survivability design.</strong> We evaluated each product's approach to ensuring live organisms reach the intestine: spore-forming strains, acid-resistant encapsulation, CFU guaranteed at expiration versus manufacture, and storage stability data. Products relying on fragile, non-encapsulated Lactobacillus in a gummy format were scored lower for viability confidence.</li>
        <li><strong>Reviewed clinical evidence for specific strains.</strong> We searched PubMed for randomized controlled trials on each product's specific probiotic strain(s) and dose. Products using strains with published human clinical data at the dose provided in the gummy received significantly higher evidence scores than those using generic "probiotic blend" designations.</li>
        <li><strong>Conducted a 30-day consumer panel.</strong> Eight editorial team members used each probiotic gummy for 30 days and tracked daily bowel regularity, bloating severity, gas frequency, and subjective digestive comfort on standardized scales. Products were randomized with 2-week washout periods between testing.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated cost per billion CFU.</strong> We computed the cost per billion viable CFU to normalize value comparisons across products with different CFU counts. A $20 product with 5 billion CFU guaranteed at expiration delivers better value than a $15 product with 10 billion CFU at manufacture that may contain only 2-3 billion by the time you take it.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

