    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Probiotic Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do probiotic gummies actually work?</summary>
      <p>Probiotic gummies can be effective when they contain clinically studied strains at evidence-based doses. The key challenge is bacterial survivability — heat, moisture, and sugar in gummy manufacturing can kill organisms before consumption. Products using spore-forming strains (Bacillus coagulans) or acid-resistant strains (LGG) deliver more viable organisms to the intestine. A 2019 systematic review found a 62% reduction in antibiotic-associated diarrhea and significant IBS improvement, but only with specific strains at proven doses.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many CFU do I need in a probiotic?</summary>
      <p>Most clinical studies use 1-10 billion CFU per day. The optimal count depends on the specific strain: LGG is effective at 1-10 billion CFU, S. boulardii at 250mg-500mg. Higher counts are not necessarily better — a 50 billion CFU product with unstudied strains is less effective than 1 billion CFU of a clinically validated strain. The most important factor is whether organisms arrive alive in the intestine.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take probiotics with food or on an empty stomach?</summary>
      <p>Research suggests taking probiotics with a meal or within 30 minutes of eating. A 2011 study found probiotic survival was highest when taken with food containing some fat, which buffers stomach acid from pH 1.5 to 3-5. However, spore-forming probiotics (Bacillus coagulans) are naturally acid-resistant and can be taken anytime. For standard Lactobacillus strains, taking with a meal optimizes survival.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do probiotics help with bloating and gas?</summary>
      <p>Specific strains have demonstrated effectiveness. B. infantis 35624 reduced bloating by 44% vs. placebo in IBS patients. L. plantarum 299v reduced flatulence and abdominal pain in a randomized trial. However, probiotics can temporarily increase gas during the first 1-2 weeks as the microbiome adjusts. This typically resolves without intervention. If bloating persists beyond 2-3 weeks, switch to a different strain.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between probiotics and prebiotics?</summary>
      <p>Probiotics are live microorganisms that provide health benefits when consumed adequately. Prebiotics are non-digestible fibers (inulin, FOS, GOS) that feed beneficial gut bacteria already in your intestine. A supplement combining both is called a synbiotic — the prebiotic feeds the probiotic, improving survival and colonization. Several products in our guide include prebiotic fiber for this synbiotic benefit.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can probiotics help with immune function?</summary>
      <p>Yes — approximately 70% of the immune system resides in gut-associated lymphoid tissue. A 2015 Cochrane review of 3,720 participants found probiotic supplementation reduced acute respiratory infections by 47% and shortened illness duration by 1.89 days. LGG and L. casei are the most studied strains for immune benefits, working through secretory IgA stimulation and natural killer cell enhancement.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do probiotic gummies need to be refrigerated?</summary>
      <p>Most probiotic gummies are shelf-stable. Spore-forming strains (Bacillus coagulans, B. subtilis) are inherently heat-stable because the endospore protects the organism. Traditional Lactobacillus strains are more fragile, but gummy manufacturers use either spore-forming strains or specially encapsulated strains for shelf stability. Always check the label for storage instructions. Store in a cool, dry place away from direct sunlight.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long should I take probiotics to see results?</summary>
      <p>The timeline varies by health outcome. Acute digestive symptoms respond within 24-72 hours. General regularity improves within 1-2 weeks. IBS symptoms typically require 4-8 weeks. Immune benefits build over 2-3 months. Important: probiotic organisms generally do not permanently colonize the adult gut — they work while passing through and need continuous consumption. Benefits typically diminish within 1-3 weeks of stopping.</p>
    </details>

